text: The New York State School Report Card is an important part of the Board of Regents
label: BODY

text: effort to raise learning standards for all students. It provides information to the public on student
label: BODY

text: performance and other measures of school and district performance. Knowledge gained from the
label: BODY

text: school report card on a school’s strengths and weaknesses can be used to improve instruction and
label: BODY

text: The New York State School Report Card consists of three parts: the Overview of School
label: BODY

text: Performance in English Language Arts, Mathematics, and Science and Analysis of Student
label: BODY

text: Subgroup Performance, the Comprehensive Information Report, and the School Accountability
label: BODY

text: Report. The Overview and Analysis presents performance data on measures required by the
label: BODY

text: federal No Child Left Behind Act: English, mathematics, science, and graduation rate.
label: BODY

text: Performance data on other State assessments can be found in the Comprehensive Information
label: BODY

text: Report. The School Accountability Report provides information as to whether a school is making
label: BODY

text: adequate progress toward enabling all students to achieve proficiency in English and
label: BODY

text: State assessments are designed to help ensure that all students reach high learning
label: BODY

text: standards. They show whether students are getting the foundation knowledge they need to
label: BODY

text: succeed at the elementary, middle, and commencement levels and beyond. The State requires
label: BODY

text: that students who are not making appropriate progress toward the standards receive academic
label: BODY

text: In the Overview, performance on the elementary- and middle-level assessments in
label: BODY

text: English language arts and mathematics and on the middle-level science test is reported in terms
label: BODY

text: of mean scores and the percentage of students scoring at each of the four levels. These levels
label: BODY

text: indicate performance on the standards from seriously deficient to advanced proficiency.
label: BODY

text: Performance on the elementary-level science test is reported in terms of mean scores and the
label: BODY

text: percentage of students making appropriate progress. Regents examination scores are reported in
label: BODY

text: four score ranges. Scores of 65 to 100 are passing; scores of 55 to 64 earn credit toward a local
label: BODY

text: diploma (with the approval of the local board of education). Though each elementary- and
label: BODY

text: middle-level assessment is administered to students in a specific grade, secondary-level
label: BODY

text: assessments are taken by students when they complete the coursework for the core curriculum.
label: BODY

text: Therefore, the performance of students at the secondary level is measured for a student cohort
label: BODY

text: rather than a group of students at a particular grade level. Students are grouped in cohorts
label: BODY

text: according to the year in which they first entered grade 9.
label: BODY

text: The assessment data in the Overview and Analysis are for all tested students in the school,
label: BODY

text: including general-education students and students with disabilities. In the Overview, each
label: BODY

text: school’s performance is compared with that of schools similar in grade level, district resources,
label: BODY

text: and student needs as indicated by income and limited English proficiency (LEP) status. Each
label: BODY

text: district’s performance is compared with that of all public schools statewide. In the Analysis,
label: BODY

text: performance is disaggregated by race/ethnicity, disability status, gender, LEP status, income

text: Historically, on State assessments the average performance of Black, Hispanic, and Native
label: BODY

text: American students has been lower than that of White and Asian students.  Similarly, students from low-
label: BODY

text: income families have not performed as well as those from higher income families. A high priority of the
label: BODY

text: Board of Regents is to eliminate these gaps in student performance. In addition, Title I of the federal
label: BODY

text: Elementary and Secondary Education Act includes explicit requirements “to ensure that students
label: BODY

text: served by Title I are given the same opportunity to achieve to high standards and are held to the same
label: BODY

text: high expectations as all students in each State.”
label: BODY

text: This section of the school report card provides performance data for two years by racial/ethnic
label: BODY

text: group, disability status, gender, English proficiency status, income level, and migrant status. The
label: BODY

text: purpose of the student subgroup analyses is to determine if students who perform below the standards
label: BODY

text: in any school tend to fall into particular groups, such as minority students, limited English proficient
label: BODY

text: students, or economically disadvantaged students. If these analyses provide evidence that students in
label: BODY

text: one of the groups achieve at a lower level than other students, the school and community should
label: BODY

text: examine the reasons for this lower performance and make necessary changes in curriculum,
label: BODY

text: instruction, and student support services to remedy these performance gaps. If your school did not
label: BODY

text: report data for the 2002-03 school year for a subject and grade, a table showing data for subgroups in
label: BODY

text: that subject and grade will not be included in the Analysis.

text: Accountability Cohort: An accountability cohort is all students, regardless of grade status, who were enrolled in
label: BODY

text: school on BEDS day two years after the year in which they entered grade 9, or, in the case of ungraded students
label: BODY

text: with disabilities, the year in which they reached their seventeenth birthday. (For example, the 1998 accountability
label: BODY

text: cohort consists of all students who first entered grade 9 in the fall of 1998 who were enrolled on October 4, 2000).
label: BODY

text: Certain students with severe disabilities, new immigrants, and students who transfer to programs leading to a high
label: BODY

text: school diploma or high school equivalency diploma are not included in the school accountability cohort. Cohort is
label: BODY

text: defined in Section 100.2 (p) (8) of the Commissioner’s Regulations.
label: BODY

text: Component Retests: Component retests were offered in Regents English and Mathematics A to graduating
label: BODY

text: seniors who were at risk of not meeting the State learning standards. Component retesting is the process by which
label: BODY

text: a student who has failed a Regents examination in English or Mathematics A twice is retested only on the areas of
label: BODY

text: the learning standards in which the student has been proven deficient. Component retesting eliminates the need for
label: BODY

text: the student to retake the full Regents examination multiple times. Students who earn credit through component
label: BODY

text: retesting are counted as if they scored in the 55–64 range or in the 65–84 range, as determined by the results of
label: BODY

text: Limited English Proficient (LEP) Students: Schools provide special English instruction to students for whom
label: BODY

text: English is a second language so they can participate effectively in the academic program. In 2002–03 and in
label: BODY

text: previous years, students were considered LEP if, by reason of foreign birth or ancestry, they spoke a language
label: BODY

text: other than English and (1) either understood and spoke little or no English or (2) scored at or below the 40th
label: BODY

text: percentile on an English language assessment instrument. The United States Department of Education has
label: BODY

text: approved the use of the New York State English as a Second Language Achievement Test (NYSESLAT) as the
label: BODY

text: required measure of language arts proficiency for LEP students in grades 4 and 8 who have attended school in the
label: BODY

text: United States (not including Puerto Rico) for fewer than three consecutive years and for LEP students who have
label: BODY

text: attended for four or five years and have received an exemption from the general assessment requirement.
label: BODY

text: Student Confidentiality/Suppressed Data (# and s): To ensure student confidentiality, the Department does not
label: BODY

text: publish data for groups with fewer than five students or data that would allow readers to easily determine the
label: BODY

text: performance of a group with fewer than five students. In the Overview, the pound character (#) appears when fewer
label: BODY

text: than five students in a group were tested. In the Analysis, when fewer than five students in a group (e.g., Hispanic)
label: BODY

text: were tested, percentages of tested students scoring at various levels are suppressed for that group and the next
label: BODY

text: smallest group.  Suppressed data are indicated with an (s).  However, the performance of tested students in these
label: BODY

text: groups is aggregated and shown in the Small Group Total row.
label: BODY

text: Validity and Reliability of Small Group Data: It is important that programmatic decisions are based on valid and
label: BODY

text: reliable data. Data for fewer than 30 students in a group may be neither valid nor reliable.  If a school does not have
label: BODY

text: 30 students in a grade or a subgroup in a given year, the school should evaluate results for students in this group
label: BODY

text: over a period of years to make programmatic decisions.
